nce against our own self-initiated actions. If hammering is the action, we find "nails" and "non-nails." Actions in turn express a self-organizing process rooted in motivational structures that presuppose values. These patterns of motivation therefore prefigure the shape of what we think or perceive. But the emotions, feelings, "sensings" through which we discern motivation are never just about what they seem, especially given ample incentives to distortion and self-deception. The "trigger" is the tip of an iceberg. This book works toward a coherent method for getting at the basement level of the action trajectories that motivate exploration, selective attention, and thus interpretations of reality—a crucial question in an age of motivated disinformation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aConsciousness. 0aMotivation (Psychology). 0aPhenomenology. 4aPhilosophy : Hermeneutics. 4aPhilosophy : Phenomenology. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Social Philosophy. 4aPsychology : Psychology. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Spirituality. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Mind & Body.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2023z978311149193640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849473940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438494739423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438494739/original  a978-3-11-149193-6  SUNY Press eBook Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles